['when i asked it write code it said it cant', 'Can chatgpt make a code to crash any windows?', 'People appear to be too easily taken in by ChatGPT.  Much of what it does isn\'t in the least miraculous.  In this particular example, you can Google this code and find pretty much the exact same code, including the comments.  It looks like ChatGPT did that and then did a little editing on the comments.\nIf you ask ChatGPT for an essay, the essay is very formulaic.  If you read a few of them, they all begin to sound the same.  I messed around with doing some queries and eventually got ChatGPT to write a sonnet comparing Donald Trump to a chicken.  But there was nothing particularly original about the sonnet.  It was kind of a clever word salad in sonnet format.  No doubt something of a striking accomplishment in its generality, but to call this Artificial Intelligence, as the general public understands that term, is a bit of a stretch.  What it does is clever, in a sense, but it is not in any way "intelligent".  It just has a giant database (the internet) and is clever about mish-mashing that data together in a way that easily fools people into thinking that it actually "knows" something.', 'Thank you very much for your work. It is really amazing how clear it is!\r\nSuggestion of video: Teach, step by step, how to convert a r shiny app into a PWA.', 'would they start charging for this soon?', 'Your experience is very best. I learned alot from you. Can you make a video on kennard stone algorithm ?', 'Just yesterday, I created an entire analysis using chatgpt. From csv readting, eda - generates 10 plots for me without specifiying what I want, also data wrangling and chunking my dataset to multiple csv. it was fun. I learned a lot.', "I haven't really done a deep dive into ChatGPT yet (guess I'm always fashionably late to the party), but this gives me a compelling reason to take a look. I've seen some buzz around code writing capabilities, but I really had to see to believe. While this is a simple example, it's certainly non trivial and suggests the network has some kind of understanding of Python and its underlying frameworks. Thanks Professor!"]

["He doesn't show that Meta has a full stack dev options - he only shows the different courses that Meta has on Coursera which anyone can read and find.", 'Wow, all this time i just learned on YouTube, didn't know there are some courses from Meta, cover both Backend and frontend . Love you content :"3', 'None of these certificates are actually fully available yet.
I'm already a developer so went through the first few courses really fast. Once I'm past those, it tells me that the rest of the courses are only going to be released in January(!). Expecting me to pay for Coursera until then. 

What buggs me is that nobody has finished any of the meta certificates, because none of them are complete. Yet people keep talking about how great they are, and some keep claiming they even finished them just to drive affiliate links.

Really disappointed at how YouTubers keep pushing these courses without being aware of their incompleteness of them. Sure Coursera is guilty as well, but I feel a bit betrayed tbh. If nobody finished these courses, how are you gonna know how good the more advanced parts are? Or the "job platform" we are promised? 

I put actual time into these courses, fully believing that I can get those certificates within a couple days/weeks so I can add them to my CV. 


The earliest anyone can finish any of these courses is in February 2023(!), as the last course will only become available on the 31st of January. Sure I can wait until then, but if I would've known - I would've worked on the IBM cert instead for example.

I know you aren't claiming the courses are complete in this video, but I think it's a crucial piece of information everyone considering these certs has to consider. 


If you are a new developer it's totally fine, as by the time you'll be done with the first few courses, you'll be able to do the others. The quality of the first few courses was great, no complaints there.', 'I asked for the financial aid a few days ago [ for the back-end Meta cert] but I am also interested in learning UI/UX. The whole point of the Jupyter notebook as both an execution environment and a sort of copy of the physical notebook in the lab is that you're supposed to record what your experiments...the successes and the failures. You're supposed to make and write down hypotheses, see if they're correct. Make notes about what you learn, what you need to look into more. You need to bring domain knowledge to bear on the topic. Otherwise, it's just not science. EDA should be principled and methodical; not a free for all.

In that respect. Mito is much better because it at least generates the code, which you should save, so you have reproducibility.
